@officialsomebdy So to answer your question, no. There isn't a single thing about applying human rights that could compare to slavery... except to say no human rights were given to Black People during the long and painful process of slavery.

@officialsomebdy Lastly, I suggest not attempting to compare slavery to different ways to pay employees. Slavery was brutal forced labor upon specifically Black People for centuries (in this country and others) without any such compensation.

@officialsomebdy include this very basic expansion. Doctors are paid well in Northern European countries, in Cananada and even in Great Britian (which has had a national health service for a while that has been protected by conservatives there for years).

@officialsomebdy Eventually, the "Right to privacy" as well as other modern concepts were accepted by the people. Currently, most advanced countries have realized that all people deserve to have all their basic needs met.¬† It makes zero sense for the supposed "richest nation in the world"
@officialsomebdy Later on, the "Right to freedom of thought, religion expression" were also realized and applied in different societies including our own.

@officialsomebdy I appreciate your question! So the overall widely agreed upon definition of Human Right is: "A right that is believed to belong justifiably to every person". It's important to know that prior to understanding why human rights are added upon the futher in history we go.
